            but he really was probably not

    SPECIAL NEEDS DOCTRINE

        EXAM analysis:

            1- has the gov articulated a special [regulatory] need beyond traitional law enforcement? [investigation, evidence-gathering]
            2- Three-part breakdown:
                what is the the government interest?
                how effective is the fit between the program and its goal?
                how significant is the intrusion on personal liberty?

        Border Searches

        Inventory Searches

            to protect property rights of the suspects
            police safety

                BERTINE
                LAFAYETTE

            no PC req except for the PC needed for the predicate arrest

            only req is standard procedures

        Admin Searches

            do not need pc
            do not need RS
            reasonable admin scheme is sufficient

        Jail Searches

            florence

                disease control
                ID gang affiliations
                contraband detection

        BURGER

            closely regulated business
            no PC needed
            reqs:

                subs gov interest
                inspections nec
                adequate statutory scheme
                    provides notice
                    limits discretion

        PATEL

            I was on call

        BORDER SEARCHES

            MARTINEZ FUERTE

                suspicionless border checkpoint searches are permissible
                you can even disassemble a gas tank at the border (flores-montano)

            RS req if significantly more intrusive (montoya de hernandez)
                16 hour detention at border on RS

            roving patrols
                stop and frisk car RS
                search car PC

        PROUSE and SITZ

            both sobriety checkpoints
            req: constrain officer discretion with REGULARIZED PROCEDURES
            key distinction: is the purpose DETERRENCE or CATCHING criminals?

Day 15
03/07/2016

    EDMOND

        drug checkpoint case
        by this point, a sobriety checkpoint is ok as long as the purpose is deterrence
            [regulatory is ok, catching drunks is not]
        this is a no go bc trad law enforcement purpose

    LIDSTER

        cops are trying to find info on a hit-and-run
        checkpoint stop is short, involves only a few questions
        they're looking for witnesses
        and handing out fliers

        Analysis:

            Step One:

                Has the gov articulated a [regulatory] SPECIAL NEED beyond traditional law enforcement?

                    the court IDs a special need here bc they're looking for help from the public

                    they're not looking for the suspect, they're looking for witnesses

            Step Two:

                HOW IMPORTANT is the interest?

                    the court would say this is a serious crime investigation, strong interest

                how well does the stop advance the purpose? FIT

                    same time and same place as hit and run, so ct sees good fit

                how strong is the degree of the INDIVIDUAL'S LIBERTY INTEREST?

                    court minimizes this.  not intrusive, not asking them to get out.

    SCHOOL CASES

        no need to establish a problem with the subgroup you want to test

    EARLS

        suspicionless drug-test of students in extra-curricular programs is permissible

    TLO

        probably RS is req for a search of any given student


    SAFFORD

        age, sex, seriousness of crime, and intrusiveness all factor in
        the strip search is too much even with RS

    DRUG TESTING CASES

    VON RAAB

        gov interest in separating drug enforcement officers and drug consumer
        justifies drug test
        as a condition of employment

    SKINNER

        drug test for rail employees in accident or safety rules situations ok

    CHANDLER

        drug testing for candidates for public office
        they fail to establish a problem with the subgroup they want to test
        the system doesnt even work that well, it's an easy system to game

    FERGUSON

        there was a search
            bc the testing was performed by a gov actor
            bc there's a urine sample handed to a nurse and then to law enforcement
                C/A: analogize to greenwood and to hoffa and the informant cases
        it did not comply with the req of the 4th
            bc it didnt hold up under the special needs analysis

            special need would be public health

                but the short term means are traditional law enforcement

    MARYLAND v KING

        DNA sampling case

        there was a search

            two actually:
            the cheek swab (hicks jones TRESPASS onto the person, REOP squeeze cases)
            the search of his DNA once it's in the db

        compliance with warrant

            no warrant, no warrant exception
            not a special needs case bc trad law enforcement purpose
            therefore this is a totality of the circumstances / reasonableness case

                which plays just like the special needs analysis, except without step one

            BALANCING THE INTERESTS

                gov has interests:

                    -ID those in custody
                        (though this is BS bc delays and db is full of unsolved cases)
                    -SECURITY of the facility, cite florence
                        (fails for similar reasons)
                    -availability for trial: FLIGHT RISK and bail setting
                    -dangerousness inquiry in BAIL DETERMINATION
                    -EXONERATING the wrongly convicted

                fit analysis:

                    objections above undercut fit
                    the delays are the big problem
                    MAJ upholds for the following reasons:

                        -this is 21stC version of fingerprinting
                        -this is terrifically ACCURATE
                        -the process is LIMITED:
                            tested (published) population is limited to those convicted
                            judge reviews
                            limited to violent offenders
                            limited to DNA that IDs and not DNA that speaks to health

                privcy interest:

                    cheek swab minimally invasive physically, says ct
                    the search only IDs person, not facts of person's health
                    arrestee has a reduced EOP

Day 16
03/21/2016

    Maryland v King

        is not really a special needs case bc the gov cannot articulate a need beyond traditional law enforcement investigation

        Maj skips the special need part of the special needs analysis

        jumps right into balancing interests

            Gov interests:

                ID
                safety
                discouraging flight
                bail determination
                exoneration

            fit:

                accuracy of DNA
                limited population

            individual's interest:

                minimal physical intrusion
                diminished expectation of privacy
                processing/retention of DNA reasonable

        this case is similar to special needs but is not one bc they articulated no special need

            maybe its more like the probationer/parolee cases

    SAMSON

        cops stop him, dispel initial suspicion for stop, cops search him anyhow

        RULE: cops can stop and search a parolee without warrant or suspicion of wrongdoing

            they have a REDUCED EOP and that affects the reasonableness analysis, but it is still a search

            a parolee is finishing his sentence while released (here)
            a probationer is being supervised instead of a sentence

            first case where a cop can make a suspicionless search without any of the regular procedures that normaly constrain suspicionless searches

            this is another totality of the circumstances case

             police, suspicionless, totality

        GRIFFIN

            probation case
            discussed within samson

            it's a special needs case

            there's an interest in supervising the probationer's reintegration into society
            the probation officer does the search in this case
            RS

            probation officers, RS, Special needs

        KNIGHTS

            probation case
            discussed within samson

            not a special needs case

            search is done by cops
            totality of the circumstances
            RS

            police, RS, totality

            PROBATIONERS:

                reduced liberty expectation
                reduced expectation of privacy

        Analysis:

            important gov interest:

                overwhelming interest in supervising risky population
                reintegration
                eliminating recitivism

            fit:

                limited to risky populations
                evidence of impact on recitivism

            intrusion on individual interest:

                probationers-diminished
                parolees-severely diminished
                both have notice of the search condition of release

    POLICE USE OF FORCE

        generally a fact-bound inquiry, very murky
        no bright line rules
        these are hard for cops to evaluate
            court is reluctant to second-guess

    TENNESSEE v GARNER

        kid burglary suspect fleeing cops gets shot in the back of the head

        RULE: a cop can use deadly force only if it is necessary to prevent the escape of a suspect that poses a significant threat of death or serious harm. cop must have PC

            old common law rule: cop can use deadly force to stop a fleeing felon

            but jdxs and PDs both have prohibited it
            bc the law makes so many things felonies that were not felonies under the CL

        merely trying to prevent the escape of a suspect is not enough

        EXAM prep: add the factors here

    SCOTT v HARRIS

        high speed chase, cop rams the fleeing suspect, cripples him permanently

        RULE: a cop may ram a fleeing suspect if the chase is dangerous

        maj balances risk to suspect v risk to cops and others

        they don't use the factors from GARNER

        analysis:

            is the suspect armed or dangerous? yes. driving fast in the rain.
            severity of crime? he was guilty of speeding, but escalated bumping and jiving

            on sum, the conduct was not "clearly unreasonable under established precedent"

                therefore no 1983 violation

    GRAHAM v CONNOR

        diabetic guy runs in and out of a shop in search of OJ
        cop stops him because he doesn't like the look
        then they beat him up, determine his innocence, and take him home

        totality of the circumstances reasonablness is the std for excessive force

            facts of the case
            severity of the crime
            threat to safety
            resisting arrest
            attempt to flee
            proportionality of the force given the situation

    CONSENT CASES

        consent is cheap
        knowledge of right to refuse is irrelevant
        it only needs to be voluntary
        not knowing and intelligent

        consent must be voluntary
        waiver must be voluntary, knowing, and intelligent

    SCHNECKLOTH v BUSTAMONTE

        RULE: a prosecutor must prove that consent was voluntary

        so, how do we define vountary?

            not as knowing
            not connected to being advised of right to refuse

            knowledge can be relevant to the totality-type analysis
                but it is not dispositive

        holding applies when:

            not in custody
            search was consented to
            voluntariness std met:

                state has burden
                
